## 3. Manual References

Store the foreign ID as a String. Join in the service layer. Never use `@DBRef`.

`@DBRef` fires one DB query per document (N+1), is deprecated in Spring Data MongoDB 4.x,
and doesn’t work across Atlas clusters. Manual references + batch loading is always better.

```java
// Entity: store just the ID
@Document(collection = "orders")
public class Order {
    @Id private String id;
    @Indexed
    @Field("user_id")
    private String userId;               // just the ID — full User loaded in service
}

// Service: single-document join
public OrderDetailDto getOrderDetail(String orderId) {
    Order order = orderRepository.findById(orderId)
        .orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException("Order not found: " + orderId));
    User user = userRepository.findById(order.getUserId())
        .orElseThrow(() -> new EntityNotFoundException("User not found: " + order.getUserId()));
    return OrderDetailDto.from(order, user);
}

// Service: batch join — avoid N+1 for lists
public List<OrderDetailDto> getOrdersWithUsers(List<Order> orders) {
    Set<String> userIds = orders.stream().map(Order::getUserId).collect(Collectors.toSet());
    Map<String, User> userMap = userRepository.findAllById(userIds)
        .stream().collect(Collectors.toMap(User::getId, u -> u));
    return orders.stream()
        .map(o -> OrderDetailDto.from(o, userMap.get(o.getUserId())))
        .collect(Collectors.toList());
}
```

